'''Amanda Louise Holden''' (born 16 February 1971) is an [[England|English]] actress and presenter. Among her roles are Mia Bevan in ''[[Cutting It]]'', Sarah Trevanion in [[Wild at Heart (TV series)|''Wild at Heart'']], and the title role in ''[[Thoroughly Modern Millie]]'', for which she was nominated for a [[Laurence Olivier Theatre Award]]. She is one of the judges on ''[[Britain's Got Talent]]'',  and has presented a range of other one-off TV shows.<ref name=Bio/>

She is married to record producer Chris Hughes, and she has one daughter. Her marriage to ''[[Family Fortunes]]'' presenter [[Les Dennis]] ended in divorce in 2003.

==Biography==
{{Unreferenced section|date=May 2010}}
Holden was born in [[Bishop's Waltham]], [[Hampshire]] to Judith Mary Harrison and Naval petty officer Frank Holden. Her parents split up when she was four and she was brought up in the village of [[Waltham Chase]], by Harrison and stepfather Leslie Drew Collister<ref>http://www.mirror.co.uk/celebs/news/2009/04/18/amanda-holden-s-dad-on-his-30-year-rift-with-the-star-115875-21288219/</ref>. She joined the Bishop's Waltham Little Theatre Company when she was nine, and credits Angie Blackford as influential in her early stage career. When she was 16 the family moved to [[Bournemouth]] and ran a small [[guest house (lodging)|B&B]] while Amanda herself studied Drama and English literature [[A level]]s with Terry Clarke and Charles Lamb at the [[Jellicoe Theatre]], now part of Bournemouth and Poole College. She successfully auditioned for the independent drama school [[Mountview Academy of Theatre Arts]] in the [[Wood Green]] area of North London when she was 18, graduating in July 1994.

==Television career==
Her first television appearance was as a contestant on the UK game show ''[[Blind Date (UK TV series)|Blind Date]]'' in 1991, since which she has become a familiar face on British television. Holden appeared in the [[ITV]] drama ''[[Wild at Heart (TV series)|Wild at Heart]]'' as Sarah Trevanion. She is currently a judge on ''[[Britain's Got Talent]]'' alongside [[Piers Morgan]] and [[Simon Cowell]]. She has appeared on various British comedy and drama series such as ''[[Smack the Pony]]'', ''[[EastEnders]]'', ''[[Hearts and Bones (TV series)|Hearts and Bones]]'', ''[[Cutting It]]'' and as a co-star with [[Harry Enfield]] in comedy series ''Celeb''.<ref name=Bio>{{cite web |url=http://www.officialamandaholden.com/biography.aspx |title=Amanda Holden Biography |publisher=www.officialamandaholden.com |accessdate=2010-05-10 }}</ref>

In April 2009, it was reported that the US network [[CBS]] had offered Holden the job of one time guest presenter on [[The Early Show]], a daytime talk show.<ref>[http://www.mirror.co.uk/celebs/news/2009/04/23/britain-s-got-talent-s-amanda-holden-lands-us-job-115875-21299592/ Britain's Got Talent's Amanda Holden lands US job]</ref>  Holden confirmed that she would host the show,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mediabistro.com/tvnewser/cbs/confirmed_amanda_holden_to_guest_host_the_early_show_117685.asp?c=rss|title=Confirmed: Amanda Holden to Guest Host The Early Show|date=2009-05-29|accessdate=2009-05-30|publisher=mediabistro.com}}</ref> and presented alongside regular presenters [[Harry Smith (television)|Harry Smith]] and [[Maggie Rodriguez]] on 1 June.<ref>{{cite news|url= http://www.dailymail.co.uk/tvshowbiz/article-1190231/We-didnt-exploit-Susan-Boyle-says-Amanda-Holden-defends-Britains-Got-Talent-US-media-blitz.html|title= 'We didn't exploit Susan Boyle,' says Amanda Holden as she defends Britain's Got Talent in US media blitz|publisher= Mail Online|date= 2 June 2009|accessdate= 3 June 2009 | location=London}}</ref> Holden has since been signed up with CBS as a British correspondent for [[The Early Show]].

In July 2009, Holden became a [[gossip columnist]] for the [[News of the World]]'s celebrity orientated magazine Fabulous.<ref>{{cite news|url= http://www.newsoftheworld.co.uk/fabulous/celebs/417924/LIGHTS-AMANDA-ACTION-Amanda-Holden-writes-VIP-column-for-Fabulous.html|title= Lights, Amanda, Action!|publisher= News of the World|first= Gemma|last= Calvert|date= 26 July 2009|accessdate= 26 July 2009}}</ref> In January 2010, Amanda started a new three-part show called [[Amanda Holden's Fantasy Lives]].

==Acting career==
Holden has appeared in several stage musicals and in 2004 was nominated for a [[Laurence Olivier Theatre Award]] for Best Actress in a Musical for her performance in the [[West End theatre|West End]] production of ''[[Thoroughly Modern Millie]]'',<ref name=Bio/> which closed earlier than expected at the end of June 2004.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.whatsonstage.com/news/theatre/london/E8821086257644/Thoroughly+Modern+Millie+Posts+Closing+Notices.html |title=Thoroughly Modern Millie Posts Closing Notices - - News - Whatsonstage.com |publisher=www.whatsonstage.com |accessdate=2010-05-10 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.whatsonstage.com/gossip/theatre/london/E8821086888021/Modern+Millie+Cast+Defends+Holden%3F%3F%3F.html |title=Modern Millie Cast Defends Holden??? - - Gossip - Whatsonstage.com |publisher=www.whatsonstage.com |accessdate=2010-05-10 }}</ref>

She appeared in the [[ITV1]] drama ''[[Wild at Heart (TV series)|Wild at Heart]]'', alongside [[Stephen Tompkinson]]. The first series aired in 2006 and a second series followed in early 2007. Series three ran from 20 January to 9 March 2008, after which Holden left the program. She then appeared as Lizzie the Ring Mistress in the sitcom [[Big Top]] (BBC1, 2009), which ran for one series.

Holden's other TV credits include three series of the hit comedy ''[[Kiss Me Kate (TV series)|Kiss Me Kate]]'' alongside [[Caroline Quentin]], three series of the [[ITV]] comedy series ''[[The Grimleys]]'', ''Celeb'' with [[Harry Enfield]], the critically acclaimed [[BBC]] series ''[[Hearts and Bones (TV series)|Hearts and Bones]]'' alongside [[Damian Lewis]], the [[Jonathan Creek]] episode "The Problem at Gallowes Gate" and a [[Boxing Day]] special ''[[Marple (TV series)|Marple]]'' alongside [[Geraldine McEwan]] and [[John Hannah (actor)|John Hannah]]. She also co-starred with [[Bill Nighy]] and [[Sir Tom Courtenay]] in ''[[Ready When You Are, Mr McGill]]'', [[Jack Rosenthal]]'s classic comedy drama.

Holden has been cast as [[Princess Fiona]] in the West End transfer of the Broadway musical, [[Shrek the Musical|Shrek]]. The musical, based on the film series, is set to begin performances at the [[Theatre Royal Drury Lane]] in May 2011.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-10816624 | work=BBC News | title=Amanda Holden to star in Shrek musical | date=30 July 2010}}</ref>

==Personal life==
Holden married the comedian [[Les Dennis]] in 1995. They had a temporary split in 2000 when Holden's affair with actor [[Neil Morrissey]]<ref>{{cite news|title= Holden and Dennis marriage ends|url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/2609359.stm|publisher= BBC|date= 27 December 2002|accessdate= 16 July 2010|}}</ref> was exposed in the press, before eventually separating in December 2002 and divorcing in 2003.<ref>{{cite news|title= The backlash over my affair with Neil Morrissey was the worst time of my life, says Amanda Holden|url= http://www.dailymail.co.uk/tvshowbiz/article-565209/The-backlash-affair-Neil-Morrissey-worst-time-life-says-Amanda-Holden.html|publisher= Mail Online|date= 12 May 2008|accessdate= 7 December 2009|first= Richard|last= Simpson | location=London}}</ref>

On 21 January 2006, Holden gave birth to her first child, Alexa "Lexi" Louise Florence Hughes with fiance Chris Hughes.<ref>http://showbiz.sky.com/Amandas-Baby-Named-Already</ref> She married record producer Chris Hughes at [[Babington House]]<ref>Sunday Times, 10 January 2010.</ref>, Somerset, on 10 December 2008 with former [[Formula One]] racing driver [[David Coulthard]] acting as the [[best man]].

Holden ran the [[London Marathon]] in 4 hours and 13 minutes<ref>http://www.celebritygenius.com/Amanda-Holden/biography.html</ref> on 13 April 2008, in the name of the [[Born Free Foundation]],<ref name="justgiving.com">http://www.justgiving.com/amandaholden</ref> having collected public and celebrity sponsors online. She is a vegetarian.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/tvshowbiz/article-1244053/Amanda-Holden-shows-talent-staying-revealing-bikini.html | location=London}} {{Dead link|date=August 2010|bot=RjwilmsiBot}}</ref>

==Activism==
Holden camapaigned to keep a [[Sainsbury's]] out of Bishop's Waltham. Residents of her hometown later accused her of a double standard in November 2010 when signed a deal with [[Tesco]], England's largest supermarket chain <ref>[http://www.dailyecho.co.uk/news/8496533.Britain___s_Got_Talent_judge_Amanda_s_Tesco_deal_angers_traders/ Amanda Holden accused of double standards over Bishop<U+2019>s Waltham store plans
]</ref>. 

